;; 12-databases-and-indexes.slat
;; Book of CS Curriculum — 12-databases-and-indexes

(chapter
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   12
  :title            "Databases and Indexes"
  :author-lane      "lacuna-eng-audit-rebuild-2026-07-14"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 12
  :title \"Databases and indexes\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You have a spreadsheet with 100,000 rows and you need to find every
   order from customer #4472. If you scan every row, you read 100,000
   things to find (maybe) five. If you have an index — a sorted map from
   customer number to row positions — you find those five rows in about
   17 comparisons. That is the difference between waiting a second and
   waiting for a coffee.\"

  :what-a-database-is
  \"A database is a program that manages structured data on disk so that
   many queries can find what they need without reading everything.
   Databases give you: storage (data survives restart), queries (a
   language to ask questions), transactions (multiple changes succeed or
   fail together), and indexes (fast lookup).\"

  :the-two-families
  \"Relational databases (Postgres, SQLite, MySQL) store data as tables
   with rows and columns and give you SQL. Key/document databases
   (Redis, MongoDB, DynamoDB) store data as key→value or JSON documents
   and give you simpler APIs. Both families have their place. The
   choice is usually about your access pattern (do you always look up
   by one key, or do you join across many tables?) more than about
   scale.\"

  :indexes-explained
  \"An index is a data structure that maps a value to the row(s) that
   contain it. Without an index, finding row-by-value is O(n). With a
   B-tree index — the most common shape — it is O(log n). B-trees are
   trees where each node has many children (typically 100+), so the
   tree stays short even at billions of rows.

   Trade-off: indexes make reads fast and writes slower (every insert
   updates the index too) and take disk space (index files can be as
   big as the data itself). The art of database design is picking the
   right indexes for your read/write mix.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; A tiny B-tree-ish index — the idea, not a real B-tree
   (define (build-index rows key-fn)
     (let ((index (make-hash)))
       (for-each
         (lambda (row i)
           (let* ((k (key-fn row))
                  (existing (hash-ref index k '())))
             (hash-set! index k (cons i existing))))
         rows (iota (length rows)))
       index))

   (define (lookup index key)
     (reverse (hash-ref index key '())))

   ; Usage
   (define orders '(...))  ; 100,000 rows
   (define customer-index (build-index orders (lambda (o) (assq 'customer o))))
   (lookup customer-index 4472)  ; returns list of row positions\"

  :transactions
  \"A transaction is a group of operations treated as one. Either all
   succeed (commit) or none do (rollback). ACID names the four
   properties: Atomic (all-or-nothing), Consistent (constraints hold),
   Isolated (concurrent transactions don't interfere), Durable
   (committed changes survive crash). Different databases relax
   different letters for performance; understanding what your database
   guarantees is a survival skill.\"

  :cross-refs
  ((see \"04-trees\" \"why B-trees are the tree shape databases love\")
   (see \"10-compilers-databases-distributed-security-ml\" \"the survey chapter this expands\")
   (see \"Book of Systems — ch11-durability\" \"transactions in the shop context\")))
")
